Getting a Linux to practise on.

You can read about Linux all day, but you only learn it by typing. So the first job is to get yourself a Linux prompt to play with. There are four common ways, and I'll go from easiest to most involved.

The first, and the most authentic, is a cloud V-M. You spin up a small server on a provider like DigitalOcean, A-W-S Lightsail, Linode, or Hetzner. It costs a few dollars a month. You connect to it over S-S-H, which we cover in module eight, and you have a genuine Linux server that you can break and rebuild as much as you like.

The second is Multipass, from Canonical. It's free, and it gives you a one-command Ubuntu virtual machine right on your laptop. No signup, and it runs on Mac, Windows, or Linux hosts. You launch it, you shell into it, and you're in.

The third, if you're on Windows, is W-S-L two, the Windows Subsystem for Linux. It runs a real Linux kernel alongside Windows with almost no friction, and your files are shared between the two.

The fourth is a Docker container. If you already have Docker, one line drops you straight into a disposable Ubuntu shell. It's instant, but it has no systemd by default, which limits module nine, and nothing persists unless you mount a volume.

For this course, pick Multipass if you're on a laptop, or a cheap cloud V-M if you want the most realistic experience. Then stick with it. Switching environments halfway through is just a distraction.
